# Re-Imagined Strategy Report: Order Intake

1) Executive Summary — “One Big Move”
Our One Big Move is to re-platform Order Intake into a Zero-Touch Agentic Ecosystem that keeps SAP S/4HANA strictly clean-core as the system of record, externalizes all adaptive logic to a Side-Car on SAP BTP for deterministic orchestration, and introduces SAP Joule/GenAI only where perception or multi-step reasoning is required. For ANZ, we will prioritize automating unstructured intake (email/PDF/fax) and high-volume order changes, while retaining VA01 solely as a fallback exception path. The Side-Car will implement canonical validation, routing, and transformation once (not in ERP) and will also provide an adapter pattern for regional channels (e.g., Uruguay Power Street), enforcing Clean Core. Agentic capabilities will be deployed in controlled, auditable steps starting in Shadow mode to convert manual re-keying and triage workloads into machine-led tasks with human oversight.

This move directly addresses the documented pain points:
- Manual email/PDF entry into SAP {DOC1, Pain points, “Manual email and PDF order entry into SAP.”}
- Spreadsheet-based intake from DC channels {DOC1, Pain points, “Spreadsheet uploads from distribution center channels in India.”}
- Frequent change requests in ANZ {DOC1, Pain points, “Frequent order change requests in ANZ.”}
- Payload normalization for Uruguay’s Power Street channel {DOC1, Pain points, “Uruguay Power Street channel payload requires normalization before posting.”}
- Slow, manual deductions/dispute processing {DOC1, Pain points, “Deduction and dispute processing is slow and manual.”}
- Clean Core enforcement and Side-Car routing {DOC1, Regional nuances, “Keep SAP core standard and route adaptive logic through Side-Car.”}
- ANZ VA01 exception path {DOC1, Regional nuances, “ANZ VA01 is a fallback exception path, not the default.”}

2) Current Reality Synthesis
Order Intake across ANZ (and related regional practices) exhibits a fragmented channel landscape and pervasive manual handling. The result is re-keying delays, high transcription error risk, and extended cycle times for amendments and dispute-related follow-ups.

Observed As-Is behaviors and regional nuances:
- Manual order capture via email/PDF with re-keying into SAP {DOC1, Pain points, “Manual email and PDF order entry into SAP.”}
- Spreadsheet-based DC intake (India) implying heterogeneous intake maturity {DOC1, Pain points, “Spreadsheet uploads from distribution center channels in India.”}
- ANZ experiences frequent order change requests and retains VA01 as an exception path {DOC1, Pain points & Regional nuances, “Frequent order change requests in ANZ.”; “ANZ VA01 is a fallback exception path, not the default.”}
- Uruguay Power Street requires payload normalization and an external channel adapter {DOC1, Pain points & Regional nuances, “Uruguay Power Street channel payload requires normalization before posting.”; “Uruguay Power Street is an external channel adapter requirement.”}
- Deductions/disputes are slow and manual with cross-system evidence gathering {DOC1, Pain points, “Deduction and dispute processing is slow and manual.”}

Hotspots (Top 5 Item_IDs with evidence):
- P-009: Manual multi-channel order intake re-keyed into SAP. Evidence: {DOC1, Process notes, “Manual multi-channel order intake … re-keyed into SAP.”}
- P-001: Manual email/PDF order capture. Evidence: {DOC1, Pain points, “Manual email and PDF order entry into SAP.”}
- P-003: Frequent order change requests in ANZ. Evidence: {DOC1, Pain points, “Frequent order change requests in ANZ.”}
- P-006: ANZ VA01 fallback exception path. Evidence: {DOC1, Regional nuances, “ANZ VA01 is a fallback exception path, not the default.”}
- P-012: Deduction/dispute triage manual and cross-system. Evidence: {DOC1, Pain points, “Deduction and dispute processing is slow and manual.”}

Why these hotspots matter:
- They are high-volume, high-friction entry points that generate rework, delays, and errors.
- They embody both deterministic and judgment-heavy tasks—precisely the boundary where a Side-Car plus selective agentic AI provides maximum leverage.
- They directly relate to Clean Core compliance by relocating adaptive logic outside the ERP kernel {DOC1, Regional nuances, “Keep SAP core standard and route adaptive logic through Side-Car.”}.

3) Strategy: Layered Re-Imagination using Path A/B/C

Path A: SAP S/4HANA Core Standardization (Foundation)
Objective: Minimize variability in the ERP kernel; consolidate on standard S/4HANA processes while ensuring VA01 is restricted to an exception-only fallback in ANZ.

Actions:
- Enforce Clean Core and standardize core order capture/maintenance to standard S/4HANA functions, removing any custom logic from the ERP kernel. Evidence: {DOC1, Regional nuances, “Keep SAP core standard and route adaptive logic through Side-Car.”}
- Reconfirm ANZ VA01 usage as an exception-only path with governance (access controls, monitoring, and exception thresholds) rather than the default operational path. Evidence: {DOC1, Regional nuances, “ANZ VA01 is a fallback exception path, not the default.”}
- Clarify and document the standard end-to-end process paths for order creation and maintenance, and ensure change request handling defaults to Side-Car orchestrated workflows before any ERP transaction is invoked—reducing direct manual use of VA02/VA03. Evidence: {DOC1, Pain points, “Order changes are processed manually in SAP (VA02/VA03) …”}
- Keep any channel-specific transformations (e.g., formatting, normalization) out of ERP; only post validated, canonical orders to S/4HANA. Evidence: {DOC1, Pain points, “Uruguay Power Street channel payload requires normalization before posting.”; DOC1, Regional nuances, “Uruguay Power Street is an external channel adapter requirement.”}

Value:
- Reduces configuration sprawl and eliminates custom code in the core.
- Creates a stable, supportable backbone ready to interoperate with Side-Car orchestration.

Path B: SAP BTP Platform Enhancements / Deterministic Automation (Bridge)
Objective: Centralize orchestration, validation, and deterministic automation in the Side-Car for all structured and rule-based flows.

Actions aligned to specific pain points:
- Spreadsheet Intake (India, applicable pattern for ANZ where structured uploads exist)
  - Implement Side-Car intake service to validate structured order spreadsheets against canonical rules (field presence, format, master data lookups) before posting to S/4HANA. Evidence: {DOC1, Pain points, “Spreadsheet uploads from distribution center channels in India.”}
  - Standardize controls to reduce rejections and rework; ensure audit logs for all validation outcomes (Clean Core: validations outside ERP). Evidence: {DOC1, Regional nuances, “Keep SAP core standard and route adaptive logic through Side-Car.”}
- Order Change Requests (ANZ)
  - Introduce a Side-Car workflow that captures change requests, validates them deterministically (order status, pricing lock windows, credit blocks as applicable), and only triggers standard ERP updates upon successful checks. Evidence: {DOC1, Pain points, “Frequent order change requests in ANZ.”; “Order changes are processed manually in SAP (VA02/VA03) …”}
  - Automate standard changes (e.g., requested delivery date shifts within policy) and route exceptions to human review, with ERP updates triggered via standard operations.
- Power Street (Uruguay) Deterministic Normalization
  - Build an external channel adapter in the Side-Car to normalize Power Street payloads into a canonical order model prior to ERP posting. Evidence: {DOC1, Pain points & Regional nuances, “Uruguay Power Street channel payload requires normalization before posting.”; “Uruguay Power Street is an external channel adapter requirement.”}
  - Maintain transformation rules and mapping solely in the Side-Car to maintain Clean Core. Evidence: {DOC1, Regional nuances, “Keep SAP core standard and route adaptive logic through Side-Car.”}
- Deterministic Intake Routing and Controls (ANZ)
  - Configure channel-aware routing in the Side-Car to direct structured vs. unstructured content into the appropriate pipelines (deterministic vs. agentic), with duplication checks and completeness validations. Evidence: {DOC1, Process notes, “Manual multi-channel order intake … re-keyed into SAP.”}
  - For ANZ, bias first-pass routing towards Side-Car workflows before permitting ERP transactions, reducing reliance on manual VA01/VA02/VA03 operations. Evidence: {DOC1, Regional nuances, “ANZ VA01 is a fallback exception path …”}

Value:
- Eliminates re-keying on structured channels.
- Establishes canonical governance and consistency across regions without ERP customizations.

Path C: SAP Joule/GenAI Agentic AI Deployment (Game Changer)
Objective: Apply agentic AI only where perception and reasoning are essential, with explicit human-in-the-loop in Shadow phase.

Actions aligned to specific pain points:
- Unstructured Intake (Email/PDF/Fax) for ANZ
  - Deploy Joule/GenAI agents to extract order data from unstructured sources, classify content, and assemble a canonical order. Evidence: {DOC1, Pain points, “Manual email and PDF order entry into SAP.”; DOC1, Process notes, “Manual multi-channel order intake … re-keyed into SAP.”}
  - The agent submits a proposed order to the Side-Car validation workflow; in Shadow, humans review the proposal before ERP posting.
- Multi-Channel Orchestration with Agentic Judgment
  - Where signals conflict (e.g., overlapping emails and spreadsheets for the same order), an agent proposes deduplication decisions and highlights confidence scores for human confirmation during Shadow. Evidence: {DOC1, Process notes, “Manual multi-channel order intake … re-keyed into SAP.”}
- Deduction/Dispute Triage
  - Introduce an agent to aggregate cross-system evidence excerpts, propose categorization (e.g., price, freight, promotion-related), and craft a triage summary for reviewer approval. Evidence: {DOC1, Pain points, “Deduction and dispute processing is slow and manual.”; P-012 summary referencing cross-system reconciliation.}
- Adaptive Exception Handling for Order Changes
  - When deterministic rules do not fully resolve a change request, an agent summarizes the case (original order, requested changes, policy implications) and recommends an action, routed to human approver in Shadow. Evidence: {DOC1, Pain points, “Frequent order change requests in ANZ.”; “Order changes are processed manually in SAP (VA02/VA03) …”}

Value:
- Converts the heaviest manual interpretation work to machine-led suggestions.
- Ensures Clean Core by keeping extraction and reasoning out of ERP; only validated results reach S/4HANA. Evidence: {DOC1, Regional nuances, “Keep SAP core standard and route adaptive logic through Side-Car.”}

4) Architecture of the Future State

Hub-and-Spoke Operating Model
- Hub: SAP S/4HANA as the authoritative system of record holding orders and executing standard transactions (no custom code).
- Spokes: SAP BTP Side-Car hosting:
  - Channel adapters (e.g., Uruguay Power Street) and structured intake validators.
  - Orchestration workflows for order creation and change requests.
  - Agentic services (SAP Joule/GenAI) for unstructured extraction and triage.
- Principle: All adaptive logic, transformations, and automations live in the Side-Car, never in ERP. Evidence: {DOC1, Regional nuances, “Keep SAP core standard and route adaptive logic through Side-Car.”}
- ANZ exception governance: VA01 remains an exception-only spoke, invoked by Side-Car policy or human escalation. Evidence: {DOC1, Regional nuances, “ANZ VA01 is a fallback exception path, not the default.”}

End-to-End Flow (ANZ focus):
- Intake
  - Emails/PDF/Fax: Agent extracts; Side-Car validates; human reviews in Shadow; post to S/4HANA.
  - Spreadsheets: Side-Car deterministic validations; post to S/4HANA.
  - Regional adapters (e.g., Power Street): Side-Car normalizes; post to S/4HANA.
- Changes
  - Requests enter Side-Car; deterministic checks first; escalate to agentic reasoning if needed; approved changes posted to S/4HANA; VA01/VA02/VA03 only via controlled exception mechanisms. Evidence: {DOC1, Pain points & Regional nuances, “Order changes are processed manually …”; “ANZ VA01 is a fallback exception path …”}
- Deductions/Disputes
  - Agent compiles evidence, proposes categorization; routed to reviewer in Shadow; outcomes recorded in Side-Car and posted to S/4HANA where applicable. Evidence: {DOC1, Pain points, “Deduction and dispute processing is slow and manual.”}

Agent Personas
- Agent Persona 1: Order Intake Extraction Agent
  - Responsibilities: Extract structured order data from unstructured emails/PDF/fax; normalize into canonical format.
  - Inputs: Raw emails, PDF attachments, fax scans.
  - Decisions: Field-level extraction confidence; document type classification; duplication suspicion flags.
  - Outputs: Canonical order proposal with confidence scores and supporting snippets; routed to Side-Car validation.
  - Escalation Triggers: Low confidence on key fields (e.g., ship-to, material), conflicting duplicates, or missing mandatory references. Evidence: {DOC1, Pain points, “Manual email and PDF order entry into SAP.”}
- Agent Persona 2: Change Request Reasoning Agent
  - Responsibilities: Interpret requested changes, evaluate against policies when deterministic rules are inconclusive, propose recommended actions.
  - Inputs: Original order data (from S/4HANA), change request metadata, policy references (outside ERP).
  - Decisions: Whether change is allowable within policy; recommendation on approval/decline.
  - Outputs: Structured change recommendation; rationale summary; risk flags.
  - Escalation Triggers: Policy conflicts, potential customer impact, pricing implications needing human decision. Evidence: {DOC1, Pain points, “Frequent order change requests in ANZ.”; “Order changes are processed manually in SAP (VA02/VA03) …”}
- Agent Persona 3: Deduction/Dispute Triage Agent
  - Responsibilities: Aggregate cross-system evidence, classify root cause category, summarize next steps.
  - Inputs: Deductions/dispute documents and referenced records across systems (as available in Side-Car context).
  - Decisions: Likely cause category; sufficiency of evidence for resolution.
  - Outputs: Triage summary; evidence bundle; recommended routing (collections, pricing, logistics).
  - Escalation Triggers: Ambiguous evidence; high-value disputes; compliance-sensitive cases. Evidence: {DOC1, Pain points, “Deduction and dispute processing is slow and manual.”}

5) Technical Stack

System of Record: SAP S/4HANA
- Role: Authoritative repository for sales orders and changes; executes standard processes.
- Clean Core Enforcement: No adaptive logic, no channel-specific customizations in the ERP kernel. Evidence: {DOC1, Regional nuances, “Keep SAP core standard and route adaptive logic through Side-Car.”}

Side-Car: SAP BTP orchestration/automation
- Role: Host deterministic workflows, validations, routing, and channel adapters; unify controls and audit.
- ANZ Use Cases:
  - Deterministic validations for structured intake and change requests. Evidence: {DOC1, Pain points, “Frequent order change requests in ANZ.”}
  - Governance for VA01 fallback invocation and monitoring. Evidence: {DOC1, Regional nuances, “ANZ VA01 is a fallback exception path …”}
- Global Patterns:
  - Power Street adapter and normalization (Uruguay) as Side-Car capability. Evidence: {DOC1, Pain points & Regional nuances, “Uruguay Power Street channel payload requires normalization before posting.”; “Uruguay Power Street is an external channel adapter requirement.”}
- Rationale: Centralizes all non-core logic while keeping ERP clean. Evidence: {DOC1, Regional nuances, “Keep SAP core standard and route adaptive logic through Side-Car.”}

Agentic: SAP Joule/GenAI
- Role: Handle perception (unstructured intake extraction), multi-step reasoning (triage, exceptions), and recommendation generation with human oversight in Shadow.
- ANZ Focus:
  - Unstructured email/PDF/fax extraction to eliminate re-keying. Evidence: {DOC1, Pain points, “Manual email and PDF order entry into SAP.”}
  - Change request reasoning when rules are insufficient. Evidence: {DOC1, Pain points, “Frequent order change requests in ANZ.”}
  - Deduction/dispute triage summarization. Evidence: {DOC1, Pain points, “Deduction and dispute processing is slow and manual.”}
- Clean Core: Agent outputs are posted only after Side-Car validations; no AI logic in ERP. Evidence: {DOC1, Regional nuances, “Keep SAP core standard and route adaptive logic through Side-Car.”}

6) The Trust Gap Protocol

Operationalizing Shadow → Co-Pilot → Autopilot
- Phase: Shadow (current)
  - Agent Observability: Agents run in parallel; produce extracted orders, triage summaries, and change recommendations without committing to ERP.
  - Human Review: Business users compare agent outputs vs. manual results; resolve discrepancies and provide feedback.
  - Metrics:
    - Extraction accuracy per field (e.g., customer, material, qty) for unstructured intake.
    - False positive/negative rates for duplicate detection.
    - Cycle time deltas for change request processing with agent recommendations.
    - Triage correctness and reviewer acceptance rates for deductions/disputes.
  - Exit Criteria to Co-Pilot:
    - ≥ 95% acceptance rate for low-risk fields; ≥ 90% overall extraction accuracy on critical fields (targets to be validated in ANZ context; Not specified in inputs).
    - Stable routing and validation performance on structured/spreadsheet channels (≥ 99% success; Not specified in inputs).
- Phase: Co-Pilot
  - Agent acts as assistant: pre-populates entries, proposes decisions, human approves before Side-Car posts to S/4HANA.
  - Progressive Autonomy: Expand agent authority on narrow, well-performing scopes (e.g., specific customers or channels) via feature flags in Side-Car.
  - Controls: Every agent action requires explicit human approval; detailed audit logged in Side-Car.
  - Exit Criteria to Autopilot:
    - Sustained SLA improvements (e.g., ≥ 30% cycle time reduction) and low exception rates over two reporting periods (Not specified in inputs).
- Phase: Autopilot (target state for deterministic segments)
  - Deterministic flows (spreadsheets, normalized adapters) execute without human intervention.
  - Agentic flows gain no-touch execution for high-confidence cases while routing edge cases to human oversight.
  - Guardrails: Continuous quality monitors; automatic fallback to human review on confidence drops or anomaly detection.

Trust Artifacts
- Gold datasets and feedback loops for continuous learning (Not specified in inputs; implemented within Side-Car governance).
- Shadow-to-Co-Pilot progression documented per channel and per field group, with ANZ as first lane.

7) Risks, Guardrails, and Open Questions

Risks
- Data Quality Risk in Unstructured Intake
  - Mis-extraction of critical fields may cause downstream errors. Mitigation: Shadow phase with mandatory human review and Side-Car validations before posting. Evidence: {DOC1, Pain points, “Manual email and PDF order entry into SAP.”}
- Overreliance on Manual ERP Transactions During Transition
  - Users might continue VA01/VA02/VA03 habits. Mitigation: Side-Car gating and exception thresholds; role-based access; ANZ-specific adoption plan. Evidence: {DOC1, Regional nuances, “ANZ VA01 is a fallback exception path …”}
- Fragmented Regional Adapters
  - Multiple channel adapters may proliferate if not centrally governed. Mitigation: Canonical model and shared adapter patterns in Side-Car; single transformation repository. Evidence: {DOC1, Regional nuances, “Uruguay Power Street is an external channel adapter requirement.”; “Keep SAP core standard and route adaptive logic through Side-Car.”}
- Triage Complexity for Deductions/Disputes
  - Agentic summaries could miss compliance nuances. Mitigation: Human-in-the-loop in Shadow and Co-Pilot, with strict evidence bundle requirements. Evidence: {DOC1, Pain points, “Deduction and dispute processing is slow and manual.”}
- Clean Core Drift
  - Pressure to add tweaks into ERP. Mitigation: Governance board prohibits ERP custom logic; all change requests routed through Side-Car. Evidence: {DOC1, Regional nuances, “Keep SAP core standard and route adaptive logic through Side-Car.”}

Guardrails
- Clean Core Enforcement
  - All transformations, extractions, and workflows reside in Side-Car; ERP remains standard. Evidence: {DOC1, Regional nuances, “Keep SAP core standard and route adaptive logic through Side-Car.”}
- Segregation of Duties for Exceptions
  - VA01 usage mediated by Side-Car approval gates and logged for ANZ. Evidence: {DOC1, Regional nuances, “ANZ VA01 is a fallback exception path …”}
- Channel Canonicalization
  - Every channel maps to a single canonical order model in Side-Car before ERP posting. Evidence: {DOC1, Pain points & Regional nuances, “Power Street channel payload requires normalization …”; “external channel adapter requirement.”}
- Human-in-the-Loop
  - Shadow and Co-Pilot phases require explicit human verification of agentic outputs for unstructured intake and triage. Evidence: {DOC1, Pain points, “Manual email and PDF order entry into SAP.”; “Deduction and dispute processing is slow and manual.”}
- Auditability and Traceability
  - Side-Car maintains an immutable record of decisions, validations, and exceptions, binding agent confidence scores to outcomes (Not specified in inputs; aligned to Clean Core governance).

Open Questions (from inputs requiring clarification)
- For ANZ:
  - What is the default intake path if VA01 is only a fallback? Frequency and conditions of VA01 usage? {DOC1, Regional nuances, “ANZ VA01 is a fallback exception path …”}
  - Root causes and volumes for change requests; channels used for change submissions? {DOC1, Pain points, “Frequent order change requests in ANZ.”}
  - For multi-channel intake: volumes by email/PDF/fax vs. structured sources; error/rework rates per channel? {DOC1, Process notes, “Manual multi-channel order intake … re-keyed into SAP.”}
- For India (pattern generalization):
  - Which tools/systems handle spreadsheet uploads today? Validation controls in place? {DOC1, Pain points, “Spreadsheet uploads from distribution center channels in India.”}
- For Uruguay:
  - Is the Power Street adapter implemented today? Canonical normalization rules and transformations? Posting targets and hand-offs? {DOC1, Pain points & Regional nuances, “Power Street channel payload requires normalization …”; “external channel adapter requirement.”}
- For Deductions/Disputes:
  - Volumes, SLAs, error rates, and systems used for evidence reconciliation across regions? {DOC1, Pain points, “Deduction and dispute processing is slow and manual.”}

Detailed Recommendations by Path (ANZ-First)

Path A — Foundation
- Formalize a Clean Core charter and approval process for any change to S/4HANA order processes; all non-standard logic must be justified and redirected to Side-Car. Evidence: {DOC1, Regional nuances, “Keep SAP core standard and route adaptive logic through Side-Car.”}
- Establish VA01 exception guardrails: define who can trigger, under what conditions, and logging requirements; publish monthly VA01 usage metrics and remediate repeat patterns via Side-Car automation. Evidence: {DOC1, Regional nuances, “ANZ VA01 is a fallback exception path …”}

Path B — Bridge
- Build a Side-Car “Order Canonical Validator” for structured inputs (including spreadsheets), implementing:
  - Field presence/format checks and basic master data corroboration before posting to S/4HANA (no ERP custom code). Evidence: {DOC1, Pain points, “Spreadsheet uploads from distribution center channels in India.”; Regional nuance on Clean Core.}
- Implement an “ANZ Change Request Orchestrator” in Side-Car:
  - Deterministic rules evaluate change feasibility and post allowed changes directly; else escalate to agentic reasoning or human review. Evidence: {DOC1, Pain points, “Frequent order change requests in ANZ.”; “Order changes are processed manually in SAP (VA02/VA03) …”}
- Stand up a reusable “External Channel Adapter” pattern in Side-Car:
  - Instantiate the Uruguay Power Street normalization as the first adapter, with a shared ruleset repository. Evidence: {DOC1, Pain points & Regional nuances, “Power Street channel payload requires normalization …”; “external channel adapter requirement.”}

Path C — Game Changer
- Launch an “Unstructured Intake Agent” pilot in Shadow for ANZ:
  - Process email/PDF/fax channels; produce canonical order proposals with confidence annotations for human approval. Evidence: {DOC1, Pain points & Process notes, “Manual email and PDF order entry into SAP.”; “Manual multi-channel order intake … re-keyed into SAP.”}
- Introduce a “Change Reasoning Agent”:
  - Provide policy-aware recommendations for changes where rules do not suffice; maintain an approval step in Side-Car before posting. Evidence: {DOC1, Pain points, “Frequent order change requests in ANZ.”}
- Create a “Deduction Triage Agent”:
  - Aggregate evidence across systems (as accessible via Side-Car), propose category and next actions, with a mandatory reviewer approval in Shadow. Evidence: {DOC1, Pain points, “Deduction and dispute processing is slow and manual.”}

Expected Outcomes
- Reduced manual re-keying for unstructured channels and accelerated cycle times for order changes (ANZ).
- Canonical control and repeatable adapter approach (Uruguay pattern), reducing integration debt.
- Clean Core assurance with ERP stability and simplified upgrades. Evidence: {DOC1, Regional nuances, “Keep SAP core standard and route adaptive logic through Side-Car.”}

Implementation Phasing (ANZ first, then scale)
- Phase 1 (Shadow, ANZ): Set up Side-Car orchestrations for structured channels and change requests; deploy Unstructured Intake Agent in observe-only mode; VA01 guardrails live.
- Phase 2 (Co-Pilot): Human-in-the-loop approvals for agent outputs; expand deterministic automation coverage; instantiate Power Street adapter pattern for Uruguay as a global showcase.
- Phase 3 (Autopilot, selected lanes): No-touch for high-confidence intake and routine changes; agent-on-exception; continuous monitoring and governance.

Clean Core Enforcement Summary
- No custom extractions, transformations, or AI logic in S/4HANA.
- All business rules, adapters, and AI agents operate in the Side-Car.
- ERP receives only validated, canonical instructions from Side-Car. Evidence: {DOC1, Regional nuances, “Keep SAP core standard and route adaptive logic through Side-Car.”}

Closing
By executing these Path A/B/C measures, ANZ Order Intake will transition from manual multi-channel re-keying and reactive change processing to a proactive, governed, zero-touch ecosystem. The Side-Car becomes the nerve center for orchestration and controls, while agentic AI tackles unstructured intake and triage—always under Clean Core discipline and the Trust Gap Protocol to ensure safety, quality, and adoption.

